                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d51">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 832.61333/123.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Attorney General</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of Justice</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-12-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 19, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have a note from the United
                    States Attorney in New York this morning, saying that Mr. Garver, of the firm of
                    Shearman &amp; Sterling, attorneys for defendant Sielcken, had yesterday
                    notified him that he would not press the motion to set the demurrer in the
                    Sielcken case for argument.</p>
                <p>Very respectfully,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Geo. W. Wickersham</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
